<TITLE> Known BNP leaders unlikely to run CCC </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 16 (bdnews24.com) Known BNP leaders are unlikely to run against ruling Awami League's popular incumbent Chittagong mayor Mohiuddin Chowdhury. Amir Khosru Mahmud Chowdhury made it clear to journalists on Sunday that there had been no headway in deciding upon a formidable mayoral candidate for Chittagong. He told journalists, after a closed-door meeting with the BNP chairperson Khaleda Zia, that he had never desired to run for the Chittagong mayor's office. "Nor do I want to run for that office now." He said Khaleda had been charged with the responsibility of choosing an honest and sincere candidate to run for Chittagong mayor from the BNP camp. Amir Khosru, a former commerce minister and MP from Chittagong, was taking questions from the media after he, another BNP stalwart from Chittagong, MP Salahuddin Quader Chowdhury, met with the party supremo. The meeting ran well past midnight. The BNP standing committee at an earlier in the evening, immediately preceding the late night parley, had decided to participate in the upcoming Chittagong City Corporation elections slated for June 17. The tenure of the current city council runs out on June 25 and incumbent Mohiuddin Chowdhury has already indicated his desire to seek an unprecedented fourth term in office. The standing committee meeting concluded around 11:30pm after which the BNP chairperson convened the other meeting. Emerging from the last meeting, Salahuddin Quader told bdnews24.com that the task of selecting a candidate for Chittagong mayor had been given to the party chief and she would make the announcement in due tim
